# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 2012-swiss-referendums
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Helvetic Republic over several months in 1798.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Modelled after the French Constitution of the Year III of 1795, the new constitution was approved by voters.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1798-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] In some places voting took places in public assemblies, whilst in others the local councils took the decision.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in the Helvetic Republic on 25 May 1802.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Unlike the constitution approved in 1798, the new constitution, known as the Malmaison constitution, did not provide for any referendums.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] Non-voters were assumed to have voted in favour of the new constitution, a measure put in place to prevent its rejection.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1802-helvetic-republic-constitutional-referendum] As a result, 72.17% of voters were deemed to be in favour.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] A constitutional referendum was held in Switzerland in July and August 1848, the first referendum on record in the Swiss Confederation.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] The new constitution was approved by 72.8% of voters and a majority of cantons.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] In order to pass, any amendments to the constitution needed a double majority; a majority of the popular vote and majority of the cantons.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] The decision of each canton was based on the vote in that canton.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-constitutional-referendum] Full cantons counted as one vote, whilst half cantons counted as half.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland between 1 and 27 October 1848.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left emerged as the largest group, winning 79 of the 111 seats in the National Council.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] The 111 members of the National Council were elected from 52 single- and multi-member constituencies.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1848-swiss-federal-election] In six cantons (Appenzell Innerrhoden, Appenzell Ausserrhoden, Glarus, Nidwalden, Obwalden and Uri), National Council members were elected by the Landsgemeinde.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 26 October 1851.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left remained the largest group in the National Council, winning 78 of the 120 seats.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The elections were held under the Federal law concerning the elections to the National Council, which had been passed on 21 December 1850.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The 120 members of the National Council were elected in 49 single- and multi-member constituencies; there was one seat for every 20,000 citizens, with seats allocated to cantons in proportion to their population.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The 1850 law reduced the number of constituencies from 52, but increased the number of seats from 111; Aargau, Glarus, Lucerne, Neuchâtel, Vaud and Zürich gained one seat each, whilst Bern gained three seats.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The law also set the election date as the last Sunday in October and introduced a three-year term.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] The elections were held using a three-round system; candidates had to receive a majority in the first or second round to be elected; if it went to a third round, only a plurality was required.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1851-swiss-federal-election] Voters could cast as many votes as there were seats in their constituency.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1854-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 29 October 1854.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1854-swiss-federal-election] The Radical Left remained the largest group in the National Council, winning 80 of the 120 seats.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1857-swiss-federal-election] Federal elections were held in Switzerland on 28 October 1857.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/1857-swiss-federal-election] Compulsory voting was introduced in the Canton of Schaffhausen for the elections, with the canton seeing the highest turnout at 86.4% compared to the 46.5% figure nationally.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] Twelve national referendums were held in Switzerland during 2012.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] On 11 March, voters across the country were asked five questions on employment leave, second houses, building society savings, the Fixed Book Price Agreement and gambling revenues.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] On 17 June, there were three questions on healthcare, foreign policy and home buying.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] On 23 September, there were three on a smoking ban, secure housing in old age and music lessons at school.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] A final referendum was held on 25 November on the Animal Diseases Act.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] Swiss law says that any issue can be put to a referendum if it attains 100,000 signatures to do so.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The rules further state that for a measure to be nationally adopted into the constitution it has to get a majority of both votes and the number cantons that support the issue.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] 5. a vote on enshrining in the constitution that state earnings from gambling have to be used for the public interest.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] A proposal in Geneva to tighten restrictions on unsanctioned protests and to toughen fines for violations.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The measure was brought by an environmental organisation amid concern that a recent construction in mountain resorts have led to natural resources wastage and inflated property prices to the detriment of locals (about 500,000 second homes in the country are 12% of total housing).
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The general "business community" and tourism industry opposed the proposal citing claims of a breach to local and canton autonomy under the country's federalist system.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The national government also opposed the measure saying that reforms to the zoning laws since July 2011 could more effectively police overbuilding.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] Proponents of the measure suggested cantons should have the authority to grant incentives to raise what has traditionally been a low home ownership rate.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The measure, which could affect about 500 publishers who produce 10,000 books a year, did not require a canton majority.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] Previously the re-sale price maintenance regulations were revoked in French Switzerland in the early 1990s and in 2007 in German Switzerland.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The measure was practically unopposed and did not stir any public discussion, as it merely elevates to constitutional status what has already been in force according to ordinary laws and concordats.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] Campaigning for or against it did not take place.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The Geneva measure was said to be pertinent as the city is host to variety of supranational organisations such as the United Nations Human Rights Council and the International Committee of the Red Cross, which protesters mostly tend to target.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] Geneva: "protest restrictions and increased fines" – **Approved**.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The three June referendums asked voters questions on healthcare, foreign policy and assistance with purchasing homes.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] Three referendums were held on 23 September on a smoking ban, secure housing in old age, and music in schools.
[src:2012-swiss-referendums/2012-swiss-referendums] The final referendum of the year was held on 25 November on the Swiss Animal Diseases Act, and was approved by 68% of voters.
